\"We felt it was time to take a fresh look at our public safety technology strategy,\" said Denver Mayor Michael Hancock. \"Axon's suite of products, from body cameras to evidence management, will allow us to better serve our community and improve transparency.\"

Axon, formerly known as TASER International, has emerged as a dominant player in the law enforcement technology market. The company's flagship product, the TASER conducted energy device, has been widely adopted by police departments across the country. In recent years, Axon has expanded its offerings to include body cameras, digital evidence management systems, and other public safety solutions.

The new contract with Axon will see the deployment of Axon's body-worn cameras, in-car video systems, and a cloud-based digital evidence management platform across Denver's police force. The city has also expressed interest in exploring Axon's artificial intelligence-powered tools, such as its automated license plate reader and facial recognition capabilities.

\"We're excited to partner with the city of Denver and help them modernize their public safety technology infrastructure,\" said Axon CEO Rick Smith. \"Our integrated platform will provide Denver's officers with the tools they need to enhance community engagement, improve transparency, and ultimately make the city safer.\"

The decision to switch from Flock to Axon has raised some concerns among civil liberties advocates, who have long expressed concerns about the privacy implications of advanced surveillance technologies. However, Denver officials have stated that they will work closely with community stakeholders to ensure that the new technology is deployed in a responsible and transparent manner.

\"We understand the concerns about privacy and civil liberties,\" said Denver Police Chief Paul Pazen. \"That's why we're committed to working with our community partners to develop policies and protocols that protect the rights of our citizens while still allowing us to leverage the latest public safety technology.\"

As Denver's new partnership with Axon takes shape, the city will be closely watched by other municipalities across the country that are grappling with similar decisions about their public safety technology strategies. The outcome of this transition could have far-reaching implications for the future of law enforcement technology in urban areas.
